{{refimprove|date=March 2018}}
'''Lynch Syndrome International''' is a not for profit, tax exempt charity helping those with [[Lynch syndrome]]. It is recognized by the [[Internal Revenue Service]] as a [[501(c)(3)]] not for profit charitable organization and contributions to the organization are tax deductible in accordance with state and federal laws. Lynch Syndrome International, with an all volunteer staff, is the first organization of its type dedicated to the hereditary disease Lynch syndrome. The organization provides support for survivors and previvors who are diagnosed with Lynch Syndrome and for those who care for them. The international headquarters for Lynch Syndrome International are located in [[Vacaville, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NORD: Lynch Syndrome International|url=https://rarediseases.org/organizations/lynch-syndrome-international/|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== * [http://www.lynchcancers.org Official website] * [https://rarediseases.org/organizations/lynch-syndrome-international/ National Organization for Rare Disorders (NORD)]
[[Category:Charities based in California]] [[Category:Health charities in the United States]] [[Category:Medical and health organizations based in California]]

An '''Obligatory Dangerousness Criterion''' is a clause present in the [[mental health]] law of many [[developed country|developed countries]]. It mandates evidence of dangerousness to oneself or to others before [[involuntary commitment|involuntary treatment]] for [[mental illness]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Compulsory admission of mentally ill patients in European Union Member States |last1=Dressing |first1=H |last2=Salize |first2=HJ |journal=Social Psychiatry and Psychiatric Epidemiology |date=October 2004 |volume=39 |issue=10 |pages=797–803 |pmid=15669660 |doi=10.1007/s00127-004-0814-9}}</ref>
== See also == * [[Deinstitutionalisation]] * [[Duty to protect]] * ''[[O'Connor v. Donaldson]]'' (1975)
